Prasenjit Mukherjee wrote:
&gt; Thanks a bunch.  Some sort of notification mechanism (or protected 
&gt; methods from where we can send notifications) would be of great help.
&gt; 
&gt; We were trying to  figure out a way to reduce allreadySeen&#39;s  
&gt; evergrowing size. And one of the approaches we are trying to explore is 
&gt; that when a queue gets exhausted we can delete all the URLs (of the 
&gt; exhausted workQueue)  and either add an entry for the  host (effectively 
&gt; host/*) or keep a separate exhausted queue.

Interesting.

Is the size on disk the concern, or the performance? If the latter,
I don&#39;t know how much of a benefit marking the whole site as done
would offer, assuming you&#39;re using the default BdbFrontier.

The usual case is that the number of onsite links is much more than
cross-site links, and the fingerprint algorithm is designed to make
all the alreadySeen entries for a single host adjacent to each other.
So once a site is &#39;done&#39;, most of its alreadySeen entries should
stay out of main memory -- only being accessed for the occasional
cross-site link.

Still, it&#39;d be worth a try, and might offer a larger benefit in
some broader crawl scenarios compared to more focused crawls.

- Gordon @ IA


